Driving Our Needs

Healthcare across Canada is changing at a rapid pace to keep up with the changing needs of an aging population and advances in health technology. Canadians expect a Branch that will strengthen our publicly-funded universal health care system and ensure that it adapts to new challenges. HPFB must be an essential partner in working with provincial and territorial governments to make home care more available, prescription drugs more affordable, and mental health care more accessible. Our health care system provides Canadians with peace of mind, but we need to make the investments necessary to ensure it can continue to evolve and innovate.

Principles

Goals

Strategic Context

Emphasis will be placed upon IT investments that are practical, measurable, achievable, and deliver:

Comprehensive enablement of all regulatory activities for food and health products;

Clear value to Canadians and the health care and food safety systems;

Efficiencies that contribute directly to the safety of food and health products;

Replacing unsustainable information technology systems with ones drawing upon international partnering, best practices and new technological advantages.

HPFB s realization of the IT Vision and Strategies is based on a culture-shaping aligned with Government of Canada priorities such as the Speech from the Throne 2015 and Blueprint 2020

Goal 1: Modernizing Business Efficiency

Protect the Canadian Healthcare system while reducing regulatory burdens and avoiding unjustifiably innovation, stigmatizing technologies, or creating barriers to industry

Goal 2: Enhancing Data Analytics Capacity

Manage big data volumes from interactions between regulators and industry, patients and healthcare providers, broader healthcare system and research communities.

Goal 3: Enhancing Regulatory Transparency And Openness

Employ an approach offering developers and researchers open access to high-value public data including adverse event reports, recalls, device malfunctions data, and labeling.

Goal 4: Aging It

Address sustainability issues over the long term such as software availability, hardware support, and updating people skills with the necessary knowledge to service these systems.

Use of Proven Enterprise

Applications

Leverage and reuse of applications with established earned value;

Strengthen the use of "fit-for- purpose" support models;

Increase collaboration with other Regulatory partners (FDA, EMA, etc.)

Integrated Systems Approach

Focus On:

Real Time Data;

Data Veracity;

Improve Accuracy of Information;

More FTE time to tasks of business value.

Innovation

Work openly, transparently and meaningfully with Canadians, stakeholders and international partners;

Investments that support an "Anywhere, Anytime, with Anyone" philosophy

Enable modern technology solutions that support information sharing and collaboration.

Compliance with International Data Standards

Develop and maintain data standards by using open, consensus-based processes;

Ensure the use of high-quality data standards throughout the Branch

Align data standards with IT Initiatives, Policies, and Regulations.

Common Data Architecture

Optimize data flow;

Improve data context and management;

Better control over unmanaged data sources;

Consistency of methodology towards data integration.

Enable the Regulatory

Transparency and Openness

Framework

Help Canadians to better understand how and why our decisions are made.

Assist industry to be better positioned to comply with current regulatory requirements and plan for upcoming regulatory changes.

Where We Are Today

HPFB's team of more than 1700 professionals has already been busy building our knowledge base and keeping abreast of advancing technology and emerging trends. Efforts to modernize our legislative and regulatory frameworks have been ongoing and continue to advance in order to keep pace with innovation. HPFB has built strong relationships with our domestic partners and international counterparts in order to broaden regulatory cooperation and harmonize our processes. HPFB has been doing all of this while continually trying to find efficiencies and improve our service standards.

Where We

Are Headed

Tomorrow

The Health Product and Food Branch recognizes that regulating health products continues to be a globalized business linking regulators, suppliers, patients, and consumers. As the Branch moves towards regulatory regime modernization between 2017-2021, 2017-18 becomes a crucial transition period setting the stage for realizing big data and globalization-driven architectural improvements that have been the principle investment focus since 2015.

GUIDING PRINCIPLES

1)Compliance with International data standards in order to facilitate greater collaboration with other regulators (e.g ICH, HL7, ISO)

2)Establish a fit for purpose support model for enterprise applications (docubridge, RADAR, Canada Vigilance, eCES, LIMS)

3)Develop an integrated system rather than standalone components

4)Use proven existing software and systems whenever possible

5)Extract information and data from the various parts of the system into a common data architecture

6)Provide employees tools that help them connect and work with each other and to connect with Canadians, and that enhance their regulatory work.

7)Invest in tools which enable the Regulatory Transparency and Openness Framework as an integral part of our regulatory decision lifecycle.

KEY CHALLENGES, RISKS and OPPORTUNITIES

1)HPFB priorities are focused on ensuring alignment with global data standards, transparency and meeting new regulatory requirements and international commitments

2)SSC engagement continues to be an issue and IMSD is proposing scaling back of demands in support of Investment Plan priorities this puts much of HPFB strategic agenda at risk

3)Many key priorities (Drug Shortages; Drug and Health Product Register; NHP Online, MD-SAP) do not have SSC dependencies therefore not at risk

4)RMOD is working with IMSD to secure SSC commitments for effective support across five key application platforms (docuBridge; RADAR; eCES; LIMS and ArisG); this is essential for both day to day operations and to advance our strategic agenda

5)RMOD is working with IMSD on a pilot project to migrate applications to Microsoft Azure (Cloud) services to reduce the dependencies on SSC support

6)The migration to Cloud services may be the best / only approach to securing effective support for core business systems (DSTS, DPD, NHPSAS, eSAP) deemed unsupportable by SSC
